export const MASTER_BUILD_PROMPT = "# KENT WEB DESIGN — MASTER BUILD PROMPT (house rules)\n> Read this on EVERY build, alongside the client's `brief.md`.\n> Customer brief = WHAT the site is. This file = HOW we build it.\n\n## 🥇 Priority order (when rules compete, this wins)\n1. **The site MUST look premium and work flawlessly.** Must-must-must look good — never template trash. This is the job; everything else is second.\n2. **Conversion** — it drives calls/enquiries.\n3. **SEO** — critical, but it serves a site that already looks great. A beautiful site that ranks beats an ugly one that ranks.\n> A one-shot generator spreads attention across whatever it's told is \"top priority\". So: **beauty + function first, then SEO.** Don't let the SEO/QA checklist dilute the design.\n\n## Stack & delivery\n- **WordPress, custom-coded theme** — hand-built PHP templates + one shared CSS design system + vanilla JS. **No page builder** (no Elementor/Divi bloat). We hand-code for full design control and speed.\n- **Every page is a separate WordPress Page**, each with its own page template where it needs one. Keep it clean, semantic, editable.\n- **Header / top-bar / footer live in shared template parts** (`header.php` / `footer.php`) so they're identical across every page and edited in one place.\n- **Keep it lean:** minimal plugins (only what a build genuinely needs), no theme/plugin bloat — the custom theme does the work. Every plugin must earn its place.\n- **Deploy target: InstaWP, connected via GitHub** (push theme to repo → InstaWP serves the WordPress site). Staging on InstaWP.\n- **Always optimise:** compress + lazy-load images, `font-display:swap`, caching, keep it fast.\n\n## Look & feel\n- **Professional, modern, with real WOW factor.** Aesthetically pleasing, easy on the eye.\n- **Custom to each company — never a template feel.** Build the palette AND the fonts **from their logo**.\n- **Show the client's logo off** — give it a proper moment on the site.\n- **Fonts chosen per brand** to match/complement the logo (no fixed house pairing).\n- **Spacing:** NEVER push text or photos hard against the screen edge. Generous, consistent padding/margins and a comfortable max content width — always.\n\n## 🔴 No two sites alike — this is a Kent agency, not a template farm\n- **Every website MUST be visually distinct from every previous build.** We are a marketing agency in Kent — reusing the same layout, hero, section order, colours or \"look\" across clients is banned. That template feel is exactly what we sell against.\n- Each site's palette, fonts, hero concept, section layouts and motion are **derived fresh from that client's logo, trade and brief** — never carried over from the last job.\n- Before building, glance at what the previous clients' sites look like and **deliberately go a different direction** (different hero style, grid, type personality, colour mood).\n- **Use the design skills every build to push range and quality:** `/web-design` (section library + SEO playbook), `/ui-ux-pro-max` (styles, palettes, font pairings, UX patterns), `/ui-styling` (component/visual polish). Lean on them so each site gets its own considered design, not a copy-paste.\n- **The ONE deliberate constant:** the header/top-bar *structure* (width, layout, quality — the Grieve & Wife standard). Everything else is bespoke. Consistent bar of quality ≠ identical design.\n\n## 🌟 The WOW layer — how we make sites *special* (not just competent)\n> Rules make a site *correct*. This section makes it *memorable*. Every build must earn a genuine \"wow\". Don't ship flat, safe, stacked-boxes design.\n\n**Motion stack (approved — this overrides any \"vanilla-only\" wording elsewhere):**\n- **Lenis** smooth-scroll + **GSAP / ScrollTrigger** as the standard toolkit — choreographed staggered reveals, pinned sections, scroll-linked parallax, image clip-path reveals, animated counters, marquees.\n- **WebGL / Three.js** allowed for a standout **hero moment** on flagship builds (3D, shaders, particles, distortion-on-scroll) — used with intent, never gratuitous.\n- Everything **respects `prefers-reduced-motion`** and stays inside the Lighthouse-90 budget (lazy-init heavy stuff, lighter treatment on mobile). Wow ≠ slow.\n- 🔴 **NO preloaders. Ever.**\n\n**Signature moves — reach for these, not flat sections:**\n- **A signature hero:** oversized confident type, layered depth (foreground/background separation), a considered entrance animation, and scroll-driven motion. The hero is the \"wow\" — treat it as the centrepiece every time.\n- **Bold typographic scale** — big, brave headings; strong size/weight contrast; a distinctive display face pulled from the logo. Timid type = forgettable site.\n- **Depth & texture** — intentional gradients, soft glows, grain, real shadows, glass/backdrop where it fits. Kill the flat look.\n- **Editorial / broken-grid layouts** — asymmetry, overlap, oversized numbers, bento grids. Escape the centred-stacked-cards default.\n- **Micro-interactions** — magnetic/animated buttons, alive hover states, animated link underlines, tasteful custom cursor moments.\n- **Considered colour drama** — palette from the logo with one accent that *pops*; use dark sections for contrast and drama.\n- **One signature moment per site** — a single interaction people remember (a WebGL hero, a scroll-told story, a bold stat reveal). Every site needs its \"thing\".\n\n## Design process — references → directions → render & iterate\n- **References first:** each build starts from the **`DESIGN-REFERENCES.md`** file (the Jake-approved wow bar + design DNA) plus any client/trade-specific references. Reverse-engineer *why* they work; aim deliberately at that level. Never build \"wow\" blind.\n- **Show directions before committing:** present **2–3 distinct design directions** (hero concept + type + colour + mood) and get the pick before building the full site. Cheap to redirect early, expensive late.\n- 🔁 **Render & iterate — never one-shot:** build → **render it and screenshot** → self-critique hard against the wow bar (*is the hero flat? type timid? spacing mean? motion missing?*) → refine → then show Jake real screens to react to. Quality comes from the loop, not the first pass.\n\n## Assets — sites live or die on these\n- **Logo as a clean SVG** always (or recreate it sharp). Never a fuzzy PNG.\n- **Imagery order of preference:** (1) the client's **real photos** wherever they're good; (2) **premium stock** for generic scenes; (3) **AI-generated only as a last resort** — no real photo, no good stock, or a bespoke branded image would genuinely look better. AI is the exception, not the default.\n- 🔴 **NEVER AI-generate the logo or any text/lettering.** The logo is always the client's real asset (SVG). AI garbles text (see the Sunvera gibberish) — never let it redraw or approximate a logo, sign or words.\n- 🔴 **AI images are clean, text-free scenes only, always heavily overlaid.** Any AI image behind text carries a **≥70% brand-gradient overlay** so it reads as texture, never as legible/garbled content. No raw full-bleed AI.\n- **Brand-personal compositing = the RIGHT use of AI:** generate a clean scene, then **composite the client's REAL logo/brand asset on top** (HTML/CSS/SVG) for a thoughtful, unique-to-them touch — e.g. a dealership: a rendered car with the real logo on the badge; a plumber: a clean branded van. Place the real asset yourself; never ask AI to render the brand.\n- Every image optimised (WebP/AVIF, sized, art-directed). Cheap imagery = cheap-looking site, no matter how good the code.\n\n## Structure & features — the brief decides\n- **The client's `brief.md` always states the sitemap / pages** — build to it. This file sets the *quality bar*, the brief sets the *shape*.\n- **Features are opt-in from the brief:** only add a feature (booking, map, gallery, WhatsApp, etc.) if the brief calls for it.\n- **Floating WhatsApp button** — include it **when, and only when, the brief supplies a WhatsApp number.** Sits alongside click-to-call as another easy route to a lead.\n\n## Required sections (every site)\n- **HERO — a 10/10:** wow, modern, aesthetic, AND SEO-optimised. The centrepiece. Layout varies per project but always modern + aesthetic.\n- **Services section** — if it's a service business.\n- **Header / top bar** — same **width, layout and style as the Grieve & Wife build** (our house header).\n- **Footer (professional):** our page links · a short bio · the client's logo · contact info (incl. **phone + registered address**) · and at the very bottom a small **\"Built by Kent Web Design\"** credit linking back to us.\n\n## Content minimums (every site)\n- **Every service gets its own explained section** — not just a name in a list. What it is, why it matters, the benefit. Real substance (also feeds SEO).\n- **An FAQ on every site** — real, useful questions, wired up with **FAQPage schema**. Great for SEO and pre-answers objections.\n- **A genuine \"areas we cover\" section** — the real towns/areas served (matches the town-page rule; no invented coverage).\n\n## SEO — critical, but AFTER looks + function (see Priority order)\n- Sky-high SEO on every build. Unique title / meta / canonical / OG per page, schema.org JSON-LD (LocalBusiness or relevant type + FAQ etc.), `sitemap.xml`, `robots.txt`, one keyword-led `H1` per page, local + town targeting where relevant. Make it actually rank.\n- **Town/area pages:** build **one dedicated page per town the brief lists** as served — real, distinct content each. 🔴 **No auto-generated spread of thin near-duplicate town pages** (Google penalises it and it's not honest coverage).\n\n## Mobile\n- **Mobile-first, perfect FIRST time.** Spacing good, padding good, everything tidy. No messing.\n\n## Performance & technical hygiene (concrete bar)\n- **Lighthouse 90+ on mobile** — that's the pass mark, not \"feels fast\".\n- Images in **WebP/AVIF**, always with **`width`/`height` set** → zero layout shift (CLS). Lazy-load below the fold; responsive `srcset` where it helps.\n- Fonts: **`preconnect`** to the font host + **`font-display:swap`**. Subset/limit weights.\n- **Minify CSS/JS.** Nothing render-blocking. One shared stylesheet. **Dequeue anything WordPress/plugins inject that we don't use** (default block CSS, emoji script, etc.).\n- HTTPS everywhere. No console errors. **Caching enabled.**\n- **Libraries are allowed where they buy real wow** (Lenis, GSAP, Three.js — see the WOW layer) — but chosen deliberately, loaded lean, lazy-init the heavy stuff, and never at the cost of dropping below Lighthouse 90 on mobile. No random bloat \"just because\".\n\n## Conversion mechanics (every build)\n- **Sticky mobile tap-to-call bar** — an always-visible call button on phones. The site's job is calls; make calling one thumb-tap from anywhere.\n- **Repeated CTA bands** — don't make people hunt. Clear call-to-action moments spaced through every page.\n- **Form UX:** inline validation, **honeypot spam guard**, and an **on-page success state** (\"Thanks — we'll call you back\") — no ugly page reload. `tel:` links formatted correctly everywhere.\n- **Guarantees / \"why choose us\" trust block** — a standard section built from the client's **real** promises (fully guaranteed, no call-out charge, years established, etc.).\n\n## Local SEO & NAP discipline\n- **Name, Address, Phone identical everywhere** on the site — byte-for-byte. Google ranks local on NAP consistency; one mismatched format hurts.\n- **LocalBusiness + opening-hours schema**, embedded map, and a link to the client's **Google Business Profile** where available.\n- Review / AggregateRating schema **only when the reviews are genuinely real** (ties to the no-fabrication line above).\n\n## Brand finishing & pre-handoff QA\n- **Favicon + Apple touch icons + an OG share image**, all generated from the client's logo, so shared links and browser tabs look sharp.\n- **Custom, on-brand 404 page.** Footer copyright **year auto-updates**. Footer **social links** where the client has socials.\n- 🔴 **QA checklist before handoff** — tick every one:\n  - Every internal/external link works; every `tel:` dials; the enquiry form submits and the **job-type → subject** rule fires; success state shows.\n  - No console errors. UK spellcheck passed. Checked at **all breakpoints** (mobile / tablet / desktop).\n  - Unique title/meta/canonical/OG per page present; `sitemap.xml` + `robots.txt` in place; schema validates.\n\n## Copy & voice\n- **British English (UK spelling)** always.\n- Plain, confident, benefit-led.\n- 🔴 **Ban clichés / filler / waffle** — no \"no job too big or small\" type lines, no bullshit stock phrases.\n\n## Trust & proof — the hard line\n- Make it LOOK premium and trustworthy through **design quality, real proof, strong guarantees and clear value.**\n- 🔴 **Never invent reviews, star ratings, review counts, stats or accreditations.** (Fake reviews are illegal in the UK; fake accreditations are fraud and a safety/legal risk — it's the client's name on the site.)\n- New business, no reviews yet → lean on: real guarantees, real numbers, founder promise, \"be our first review\", local focus, and a killer design. That's what converts.\n\n## Goal = phone calls\n- Primary goal on most builds is **calls**. Click-to-call everywhere, prominent.\n- **Enquiry form** on every site via a **WordPress form plugin** (Fluent Forms / WPForms / CF7 — pick the leanest that does the job) with the **\"job type chosen → email subject line\"** rule. Entries stored in the WP dashboard **and** emailed to the client.\n\n## Compliance (defaults)\n- **Company info in footer:** phone + registered address — yes.\n- Privacy policy / cookie banner / GDPR consent — **skip by default**, add only if a client needs it.\n\n## Accessibility (sensible default — not heavy-handed)\n- Good colour contrast, legible text, visible focus on buttons/links, alt text on images, respects reduced-motion. Just never make it unusable.\n\n## Client-editability — WE manage (agency-managed)\n- Sites are **agency-managed**. Clients don't edit directly.\n- Changes come through a **ticket-style request system** (the KWD portal): customer requests a change → it lands with us → **we read it, make the edit, then approve/publish**. Build sites so we can action those tickets cleanly (tidy, well-structured code we can edit fast).\n\n## Repo & handoff hygiene\n- **Consistent repo naming** across all clients (e.g. `kwd-clientname`, lowercase, hyphenated).\n- **A short `README.md` per client site** — what it is, stack, how to deploy, where the form/keys live, any client-specific notes.\n- **Consistent asset naming** — logical, lowercase, hyphenated (`hero-kitchen.webp`, `logo-white.svg`), organised in the `assets/` folder. No `IMG_2831.jpg`.\n\n## Cross-browser\n- Test in **Chrome, Firefox, Safari — and Safari on iOS especially** (the usual troublemaker: `100vh`, sticky bars, form zoom, backdrop-filter). It must look right on a real iPhone, not just a desktop devtools mobile view.\n\n## Deployment\n- Push to **GitHub → InstaWP**. Staging / redirects / custom 404 handled per project as needed.\n";
